Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> @scubapanda not really

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> receiving text chat via memo is viable via the mempool

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> basically instant

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <scubapanda> Ah, ok!

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> it's a different use case, tho. Mempool isn't "permanent" or even close to "notarized"

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> but if all you care about is saying "sup bro" *right now*, the mempool

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> also, you don't need to wait for confirmations to read a memo field

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> you can just see "this has 0 confs, but it said 'time to party'"

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> the lack of confs doesn't matter in many cases. Or, you can wait for confs. The message cannot change, and you know it came from the trusted source. it just doesn't have confs

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> So as you see, "having confirmations" means something different in communications

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <scubapanda> Thanks for the explanation!

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> We will explore all these edge cases in SilentDragon, we are just at the beginning. In normal use case, you will see your friends "memo" sitting unconfirmed in your wallet, seconds after they send it, in most cases

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> you just have to wait for the time it takes the P2P network to pass data around, often <20 seconds

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> Confirmations really only mean something when they are 2, that means "notarized" and the memo can never be removed from the public blockchain

Author: Gateway#3763

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> @scubapanda all that data is in the transaction+block information, timestamps everywhere ðŸ™‚

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> we can always render things chronologically

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> regardless of online status

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <scubapanda> So when I send 25 messages in the same block SilentDragon will display them in right order.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> If you think about it, this must be the case, or nothing would work.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> Imagine a full node that doesn't exist yet

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> the entire Hush history has happened when this yet-to-be-born node hasn't existed, i.e. off-line

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> When this new Hush node starts, it must sync all of history correctly

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> So what  you describe, must work, or very basic blockchain things would not work correctly

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [dscrd-hush] <dukeleto> @scubapanda even if you send them all in the same block, they have an ordering
